The core container lifecycle.

A container moves through a small set of states, and a small set of commands move it between them. Hold this picture in your head. Starting from an image, docker create makes a container in the created state. Docker start moves it into the running state. From running, docker stop sends a signal called sig-term, waits a short grace period, and if the process has not exited it follows up with sig-kill, leaving the container in the stopped state. From stopped, docker start brings it back to running, or docker remove deletes it for good. And docker run is the everyday shortcut that does create and start together in one step.

Here are the commands you will actually live in. Docker run image creates and starts in one go, and it is the ninety-percent case. Docker p-s lists running containers, with the all flag to include stopped ones and the quiet flag to print just the I-Ds, which is handy in pipelines. Docker stop politely stops a container, sending sig-term, waiting about ten seconds, then sig-kill. Docker start brings a stopped container back, keeping its writable layer so anything it wrote is still there. Docker restart is stop then start in one command. Docker kill is an immediate sig-kill with no grace period, the I mean it button. Docker remove deletes a stopped container, or with the force flag a running one. And docker logs shows what the container wrote to standard output and standard error, with the follow flag to keep watching live.

You can refer to a container by name, either one you set with the name flag or the playful one docker auto-generates, or by its I-D, where the first few characters are usually enough. Name the containers you will talk to often, and let docker name the throwaways.

A handful of run flags show up constantly, so meet them now even though we deepen them later. The detached flag runs the container in the background instead of taking over your terminal. The name flag gives it a stable name. The publish flag maps a host port to a container port, so publishing host port eighty-eighty to container port eighty exposes a web server. The volume flag mounts storage into the container. The environment flag sets a variable inside it. The remove-on-exit flag cleans the container up automatically when it stops, which keeps dead containers from piling up. And the combination of the interactive flag and the t-t-y flag, written together as dash i-t, is the standard way to get an interactive shell, as in docker run dash i-t ubuntu bash.
